{!<p class="dnvp">!}[? if flavour_27_trigger and flavour_27_trigger_time == time: The Eastern Aid Act, introduced months ago to relieve the debts of agricultural enterprises in the east, has created tension within the coalition, as it directly contradicts Brüning’s goal of maintaining a balanced budget. The reparation tax—now obsolete due to the Young Plan—continues to be used to fund agricultural subsidies, sparking fierce protests from the [? if not lvp_formed: <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>?][? if lvp_formed: <span style="color: #FFCC00;">**LVP**</span>?]. They argue that this tax, primarily levied on businesses, is an unreasonable burden on job creators given the current economic crisis. Fortunately for Brüning, the [? if budget >= 0: budget surplus?][? if reparations == -2: pause in reparations?] has enabled him to abolish the tax while still maintaining full funding for the program. ?]{!</p>!}

