{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 5 and hugenberg_dvp: Out of all the bourgeois parties, the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span>, despite its critical lack of funds, stands the most resolute in its defense of the <span style="color: #000000;">We</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">im</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ar</span> Republic, even more so than the <span style="color: #000000;">Center</span> Party. Meanwhile, the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> has been drawn closer to Papen, as dictated by the terms of their alliance. The lines between the two parties are increasingly blurred, and a <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> member even resigned in protest over Dingeldey's refusal to take the final step and merge with the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span> outright. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 6 and nsdap_r_prussia >= 25 and not in_far_right_coalition_prussia and spd_prussia and not presidential_powers and not prussian_reichsexekution: Rumors suggest Chancellor Papen has secured the support of his cabinet and President Hindenburg for a decree authorizing a <i>Reichsexekution</i> against Prussia, justifying it with a fabricated claim of a merger between the <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span> and <span style="color: #700000;">**KPD**</span>—a lie apparently convincing enough to sway Hindenburg. It seems all it takes is a pretext for him to present the already signed decree. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 7 and prussia_leader == "Papen": An immediate legal challenge has been launched against Papen's seizure of the Prussian government, with <span style="color: #c00000;">**SPD**</span> and <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> officials requesting an interim injunction to block Papen and his appointed commissioners from assuming control. The <span style="color: #808080;">reactionary</span> court has rejected the injunction, and the main proceedings are scheduled to begin only after a three-month delay. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 7: Chancellor Papen has ordered the German delegation to walk out of the Geneva Disarmament Conference after <span style="color: #002654;">France</span> issued a strong objection to Germany’s demand for equal armament rights. Papen declared that Germany will not return to the conference unless the other powers agree to his terms. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 8 and prussia_leader == "Papen": The new right-wing and non-partisan Prussian cabinet assembled by <i>Reichskommissar</i> Papen has launched a large-scale purge of <span style="color: #c00000;">socialist</span> and <span style="color: #D3C24D;">democratic</span> officials from the civil service, forcing them into early retirement. Most of their replacements are conservatives—many of them <span style="color: #3E88B3;">nationalists</span>. The purge is particularly aimed at <span style="color: #c00000;">socialist</span> provincial presidents and police officials. An estimated 69 <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span> officials have been stripped of their power. Safe to say, the democratic bulwark has been dismantled. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if flavour_60_trigger and flavour_60_trigger_time == time: The <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span> performance, securing a minuscule [+ ddp_r +]% of the Reichstag due to its disadvantage from the lack of an electoral alliance, has sparked another round of debates over the party's continued existence. Resignation over the party's future is particularly strong within the business wing, with many members giving in to pressure to push for dissolution. [? if ddp_leader == "Dietrich": Even Dietrich has given up, announcing his resignation, but no one is willing to replace him.?] However, the party's active state organizations in their strongholds of Baden-Württemberg and Hamburg manage to persuade the party against dissolution. As a result, the party has adopted a more energetic tone, with power shared among Dietrich, the energetic Württemberg minister Reinhold Maier, and Hamburg Mayor Carl Petersen—the former chairman of the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**DDP**</span>. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if year = 1932 and month = 8 and (week == 1 or not rubicon) and unemployed >= 25 : Perhaps the global recovery is finally on the horizon. Many economists now believe the slump has bottomed out, with the Frankfurt stock exchange climbing steadily—share and bond values have risen by over 30% since spring. But this resurgence remains abstract to the millions of unemployed Germans still trapped in poverty. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 9 and hitler_right_coalition >= 50: The aftermath of the Reichstag elections and the emergence of a Black-Brown majority has initiated negotiations between the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> and the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>. The latter hopes to restrain the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> by compelling a potential Chancellor [+ nsdap_chancellor +] to govern through parliament rather than by decree. In doing so, he would be forced to consult a more conservative and dependable non-<span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> cabinet—where real power would reside. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 9: General Schleicher has presented an enticing proposal to [+ nsdap_chancellor +], suggesting the formation of a presidential cabinet that would rule by decree. In this arrangement, Gregor Strasser would serve as Interior Minister of both Prussia and the Reich, while Schleicher believes he can control the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> by taking the role of Defense Minister. However, the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> leadership's enthusiasm quickly fades when President Hindenburg refuses to appoint [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as Chancellor. Papen, deeply offended by Schleicher's apparent willingness to abandon him, has used his growing rapport with Hindenburg to undermine Schleicher’s influence over the President. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 10: Following the results of the Reichstag elections, Papen and President Hindenburg met with [+ nsdap_chancellor +] to hear his demands for the party’s participation in government. [+ nsdap_chancellor +] requested to be appointed chancellor once again—a demand Hindenburg refused. Buoyed by their electoral triumph, the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> have now officially reneged on their earlier promises to tolerate Papen. Going forward, they will pursue an all-or-nothing strategy: the chancellorship for [+ nsdap_chancellor +], or nothing at all. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 11: Papen has released the contents of last week's conversations with [+ nsdap_chancellor +] to the press, claiming that [+ nsdap_chancellor +] stormed into Hindenburg’s office to demand “total power over the state”—a violent one-party dictatorship—and was met with an angry rebuff from the president. This press release signals aims to signal the start of a counter-offensive against the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span>. But now, no party is willing—or able—to follow the chancellor into open confrontation with the extremists. Even the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> finds [+ nsdap_chancellor +]’s version of events more credible than Papen’s. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 11 and hitler_right_coalition >= 50: Coalition talks between the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> and <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> have continued, putting pressure on Papen to outmaneuver his former party in gaining the favor of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span>. Brüning, with permission from his party's leadership, has meet with the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>'s Strasser, promising support if he could convince [+ nsdap_chancellor +] to govern via a parliamentary cabinet with Schleicher as Defense Minister and Goerdeler as the commissioner of Prussia. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 12 and hitler_right_coalition >= 50: A follow-up meeting to last week’s discussion about a potential Black-Brown alliance, set up by Strasser, has resulted in [+ nsdap_chancellor +] agreeing to delay the vote of no confidence against Papen. [+ nsdap_chancellor +] also appeared to agree with Brüning’s other demands. Closer cooperation is expected in the near future, if both parties are genuine in their commitment to govern together via parliament. [? if nsdap_chancellor == "Hitler": However, [+ nsdap_chancellor +] is a great liar. ?] ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if year = 1932 and month = 8 and (week == 3 or not rubicon): Austria has obtained a League of Nations loan that is tied to a 20-year ban on Anschluss, but opposition from the <span style="color: #C8102E;">Social Democrats</span> and <span style="color: #0E428E;">Greater German Party</span> has stalled the law, before it finally is passed by a single vote. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 13 and hitler_right_coalition >= 50: The coalition talks between the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> and <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> have been called off, as Brüning grows increasingly uneasy about the grave risks involved. This decision is also influenced by his friend and our party member, Hilferding, who argued that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> would never restore parliamentary government. Hilferding also pointed out that many of Brüning's own party colleagues have fallen under <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> influence, a fact confirmed when they all but agreed to impeach President Hindenburg in the planned deal. Hilferding also remains the only one in our party to advocate for toleration of Papen's cabinet as the only means to prevent a <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> dictatorship. Brüning's goal is now to persuade the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> to give the Papen government 'a fair chance' to revive the economy. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 15 and hitler_right_coalition >= 50: The <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> and its grassroots supporters are becoming increasingly demoralized, largely due to Brüning’s semi-secret negotiations with the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>. Locally, party activists have faced the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> as violent thugs, disrupting rallies and intimidating opponents—far from the image of a potential coalition partner. Some activists are even taking up arms in self-defense, losing faith in their party and its leadership. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 16 and papen_explode: Gregor Strasser of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> has publicly opposed the party’s recent vote of no confidence and the snap elections it triggered, warning that such moves would only erode the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis’</span> popular support and squander their only real chance to seize power. In response, an unofficial faction of about sixty <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> Reichstag deputies has coalesced around Strasser—disillusioned by [+ nsdap_leader +]’s all-or-nothing approach. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if year = 1932 and month = 9 and (week == 3 or not rubicon) : General elections were held in Sweden, resulting in a great victory for Per Albin Hansson and his <span style="color: #D70926;">Social Democrats</span>, who now govern in a minority government. The <span style="color: #D70926;">Swedish Social Democrats</span> have embraced the concept of a 'people's home', a form of reformist socialism aimed at reducing class divides while working in the capitalist framework. Perhaps we should consider following their 'nordic' model? ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 17 and prussia_leader == "Papen": The main proceedings in the case against Papen’s unconstitutional <i>Reichsexekution</i> of the Prussian government have begun, with a verdict expected in the coming weeks. Yet, the historically <span style="color: #808080;">reactionary</span> leanings of the judiciary place us at a clear disadvantage—despite support from the state governments of Bavaria and Baden, who have joined us in challenging the decree’s legality. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if year = 1932 and month = 10 and (week == 1 or not rubicon) : Chancellor of Austria Engelbert Dollfuß has used the "War Economy Enabling Act", a law passed during the days of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which allowed him to restructure the Creditanstalt without parliamentary approval. While the <span style="color: #C8102E;">Austrian Social Democrats</span> have protested, Dollfuß' actions are technically legal. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 18 and papen_explode and not lvp_formed and ddp_ideology == "Right": The <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span>, in an attempt to revive their poll numbers, have outlined the concept of "national democracy," aiming to rekindle the nationalistic impulse that played such a crucial role in the German liberal movement. However, it is essentially a restatement of classical liberal ideology, tailored to appeal to a more nationalistic German middle class. The national democracy program also reaffirms the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span>'s commitment to the <span style="color: #000000;">We</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">im</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ar</span> Republic and recommends constitutional changes to strengthen it. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="dnvp">!}[? if papen_time == 18 and papen_explode and hugenberg_dvp and not lvp_formed: With its electoral alliance with the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">DNVP</span>, the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>'s freedom of action has become increasingly constrained. Their rhetoric is aligning more closely with the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, now calling for the "liquidation of the <span style="color: #000000;">We</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">im</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ar</span> system," an authoritarian overhaul of its constitution, and the withdrawal of power away from the masses. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="dnvp">!}[? if papen_time == 20 and papen_explode and hugenberg_dvp and not lvp_formed: Dingeldey and his associates are no longer content with merely renewing their electoral list connection with the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>. Instead, they pushed for a unified Rechtsblock of the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>, <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**Stahlhelm**</span>, and various industrialist and business organizations to provide cohesive support for Hindenburg and Papen. However, Hugenberg has shown utter indifference, refusing to commit to anything beyond a renewal of the electoral list connection. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 21 and papen_post_2: President Hindenburg has once again attempted to sound out the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> after the recent election results, with [+ nsdap_chancellor +] signaling his readiness to seek the support of other parties if he were to be made chancellor first. Calling [+ nsdap_chancellor +]'s bluff, the president offered to appoint him, but only if he could secure a working majority in the Reichstag and allow the president to pick the defense and foreign ministers himself. As expected, [+ nsdap_chancellor +] declined Hindenburg's proposal and suggested instead that, with emergency powers, he could form a satisfactory government in no time. Convinced that [+ nsdap_chancellor +] sought nothing less than a presidential chancellorship, Hindenburg withdrew him from consideration. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if flavour_61_trigger and flavour_61_trigger_time == time: Following another disastrous result for the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span>, a group of six former Reichstag deputies and high-ranking party members informed [+ ddp_leader +] that if a party congress—specifically meant to dissolve the party—isn't held, they would leave. However, this call has not gained much support, and Carl Petersen, former <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**DDP**</span> chairman, has used his mediation skills to prevent the dissidents from publicly announcing their break with the party. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if year = 1932 and month = 11 and (week == 1 or not rubicon): <span style="color: #00AEF3;">Democrat</span> Franklin D. Roosevelt has defeated incumbent <span style="color: #E81B23;">Republican</span> President Herbert Hoover in a landslide in the <span style="color: #B31942;">United</span> <span style="color: #0A3161;">States</span> presidential election. This is attributed by the Great Depression and Roosevelt's campaigning for a "New Deal", proposing expansive public works and government reform. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 22 and papen_post_2: Rumors are circulating widely that General Schleicher intends to undermine the very chancellor he helped install. Among his contacts, he's already being referred to as the chancellor-designate. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if papen_time == 23 and papen_post_2: President Hindenburg has commissioned [+ z_leader +] to make one final attempt at forming a majority coalition. Reporting back the next day, [+ z_leader +] confirmed that no such majority could be assembled. His recommendation was blunt: the only way forward is for the President to dismiss Papen, as the Reichstag will never accept him as chancellor. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if (papen_time or chancellor == "Schleicher") and year == 1932 and month == 12 and week == 1: The <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> has suffered yet another crushing setback—this time in the local elections in Thuringia. The results show the party lost nearly a quarter of its vote share compared to the previous state election. While low turnout may be a factor, this and three other recent local elections have only reinforced the growing sense that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> have peaked and are rapidly losing support. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 0 and chancellor == "Schleicher": Despite his ousting, Papen remains in far closer physical proximity to the President than the chancellor does. At Hindenburg’s personal request, he continues to reside in an apartment within the Interior Ministry building—just steps from Hindenburg’s own quarters—while Schleicher lives miles away in a private residence. This arrangement has enabled Papen to scheme full-time, without attracting public attention. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 0 and chancellor == "Schleicher": Once a close ally, Oskar von Hindenburg has become an implacable enemy of the new chancellor—reportedly over a tasteless joke that wounded his pride beyond forgiveness. In Prussian times, such insults could end in duels; this time, the fallout may claim the life of the Republic. Two members of the Camarilla now harbor intense hostility toward Schleicher, and are working to sway the President into reconsidering his appointment. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 0 and chancellor == "Schleicher": Shortly after Schleicher’s appointment, the <span style="color: #0A3161;">Western</span> <span style="color: #C8102E;">Allies</span>, following protracted negotiations at the Geneva Disarmament Conference, conceded in principle to Germany’s right to equality in arms. The practical terms of this concession remain unclear, but in Schleicher’s view, it opens the path toward establishing an official militia service. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 1: During Schleicher's addresses to the nation, one central theme rings clear: "Create Work!" He has revived efforts to resettle the urban unemployed on rural homesteads carved from bankrupt estates in the sparsely populated East. Although the Reichstag remains dissolved and he cannot legislate, he has publicly opposed Papen’s changes to the unemployment insurance system, presenting himself as a proponent of neither <span style="color: #C0A054;">capitalism</span> nor <span style="color: #c00000;">socialism</span>. His ideological ambiguity has earned him the nickname "social general"—a label he embraces, claiming it aligns with the army’s tradition of solidarity between officers and soldiers. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="dnvp">!}[? if schleicher_time == 1 and hugenberg_dvp: The <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>'s resurgence in the polls has led Dingeldey to become overconfident, unequivocally supporting Papen, then Schleicher, and even forming a parliamentary faction with the various splinter parties between it and the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>. While this move has bolstered their influence, it has alienated Hugenberg and the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>, on whom they still depend on as of their electoral alliance. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 2: For some odd reason, von Schleicher came to believe that nothing came of [+ nsdap_chancellor +]’s attempts to be appointed parliamentary chancellor simply because the man didn’t “at the bottom of his heart” want the office. By [+ month : month +], this suspicion had become a firm conviction; he repeatedly confided to journalists and his cabinet that the man simply doesn’t really want power. This belief is leading to Schleicher overestimating his chances of securing <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> support for his cabinet—without [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as chancellor. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 2: Heavy electoral losses for the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> in local elections have further reinforced the disillusionment of the voters who have brought the movement to prominence, many who joined and donated to the party expecting to receive the spoils of victory are beginning to despair, withdrawing their donations. Admission fees for rallies, once a major source of income at the local level, have collapsed despite steep price reductions. [+ nsdap_chancellor +]'s failure to gain the chancellorship or enter government to constructively relieve Germany's economic woes has caused further frustration among the movement. However, <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> leaders are quick to suppress any leaks of dissent or rumors of decline to the public. ?]{!</p>!}

