{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 3: The global economy is on the upswing—and with it, the erosion of the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> continues. The <span style="color: #000000;">rep</span><span style="color: #DD0000;">ubl</span><span style="color: #FFCC00;">ican</span> police force surveilling the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> in Munich has noted clear signs of disintegration. Resignations are occurring daily, membership dues arrive irregularly, and expulsions over indebtedness are increasingly common. Every branch of the party appears run down. As for morale, the police report observed: “The view that the peak has passed and favorable prospects are missed is commonly held among many members.” ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 3: Schleicher still clings to the illusionary hope that the now powerless Strasser might somehow persuade [+ nsdap_chancellor +] to allow <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> participation in his cabinet, now that Strasser has returned from vacation. Strasser’s absence from the public eye has unsettled [+ nsdap_leader +], who now fears potential backroom plots to fracture the party—especially given the eagerness of Strasser’s remaining loyalists to do just that. In reality, all Strasser does is to warn former chancellor Brüning that Papen has arranged a secret meeting with Hitler—set to take place within a week or two—to conspire against their mutual enemy: Schleicher. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 4 and nazi_funds <= 1: The <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>'s financial situation is becoming dire. Increasingly, equipment and supplies are being acquired on credit—credit that's already drying up under the weight of the party's existing debts. Tensions have begun to flare between the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**SA**</span> and the party leadership over how to divide dwindling donations, with some members resorting to begging in the streets or organizing lotteries to scrape together funds. One more election, and the party could face a full-blown financial crisis. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 4: Despite promising President Hindenburg not to publicly criticize his favored former chancellor, Schleicher has done just that in a bid to distance himself from the deeply unpopular Papen. Hindenburg, displeased by the breach of trust, grows increasingly estranged from Schleicher. Papen, for his part, has shown little outward hostility toward his ouster—carefully masking his resentment and thirst for revenge beneath a façade of cordiality. In the meantime, Hindenburg has quietly authorized him to serve as his secret liaison to [+ nsdap_leader +]. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 4: Günther Gereke, the energetic special commissioner for public works, has grown frustrated with the chancellor after a request for intervention to clear bureaucratic obstacles was flatly rejected. His ambitious projects remain stalled. Gereke, disillusioned, has confided his disappointment to his close friend—none other than Oskar von Hindenburg. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if (papen_time or chancellor == "Schleicher") and year == 1933 and month == 1 and week == 1: The campaign for the Landtag elections in the microscopically small Free State of Lippe has begun, with the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> investing a substantial amount of resources to sway just a hundred thousand voters. However, despite its small size, a victory here could dispel the growing belief that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> are on the brink of a catastrophic decline. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 5: At a private dinner with journalists, Chancellor von Schleicher repeatedly expressed confidence that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> leader would eventually come around to tolerating his cabinet—despite [+ nsdap_leader +]’s public affirmations of an all-or-nothing course. This, even as Schleicher made clear he would dissolve the Reichstag if needed, a move he believes would cost the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> further seats (though he seeks to avoid such a step, fearing the <span style="color: #700000;">**Communists**</span> would benefit most from their collapse). “They’ll soon be eating out of my hand,” were the chancellor’s exact words that evening. What Schleicher fails to grasp is that [+ nsdap_leader +] is no ordinary politician. He will not respond rationally, nor prudently, to Strasser’s break or to the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>’s electoral collapse. He believes destiny is on his side. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="other">!}[? if schleicher_time == 5: Chancellor von Schleicher and his press secretary have deliberately “leaked” plans to appoint Strasser as Vice Chancellor, Interior Minister, and Minister-President of Prussia, alongside naming the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> labor leader Stegerwald as Labor Minister. The Agriculture and Economics Ministries were reportedly reserved for Hugenberg himself. It’s highly likely this is a bluff—an attempt to pressure the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> into dropping its total opposition, lest they risk being sidelined entirely. ?]{!</p>!}

{!<p class="dnvp">!}[? if schleicher_time == 5 and hugenberg_dvp: With Dingeldey's pretentiousness, fueled by the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>'s uptick in polling, elevating it to the lead party on the "moderate" Right, Hugenberg is growing increasingly irritated by their independence and seeks to terminate their electoral alliance if new elections are called. While the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> still hopes to renew the alliance, they begin exploring the possibility of an accommodation with the <span style="color: #D3C24D;">**[+ ddp_name +]**</span> and the bourgeois parties as a safeguard against near-certain annihilation if Hugenberg severs ties. Meanwhile, the DNV (German National Association), a non-partisan organization aiming to consolidate the German middle, is starting to repair its relations with the liberals after already securing the support of the non-liberal right, with politicians like Treviranus. ?]{!</p>!}

